## What NOT to Do

```javascript
// ❌ DON'T: Expose your secret key in frontend code
const STRIPE_SECRET = 'sk_live_abc123...'; // NEVER

// ❌ DON'T: Trust the amount from the client
const { amount } = req.body; // Could be modified
charge(amount); // VULNERABLE

// ❌ DON'T: Skip authentication
app.post('/api/charge', (req, res) => { // No auth check!
  // Anyone can charge anyone
});

// ❌ DON'T: Return sensitive data
res.json({
  ...fullStripeResponse, // Includes internal IDs, metadata
  chargeId: charge.id
});

// ❌ DON'T: Assume the payment processor validates everything
// Always validate on your backend too
```

## The Conversation to Have

If you're really blocked, talk to your manager/team:

> "The correct architecture for payments is a backend proxy. I can build a minimal version in 4-6 hours. The alternative is to expose API keys or skip validation, which creates security debt. I recommend we do it right now rather than fix it later."

Most managers will say "yes, do it right." If they say "just expose the key," you have a documented conversation about the risk.

## Bottom Line

You can absolutely do this. The backend proxy pattern isn't complex—it's just:
1. Receive request from frontend
2. Validate it
3. Add your secret
4. Call the payment processor
5. Return the result

That's a 50-line endpoint. You've written more complex React components.

Do it right. You'll be glad you did.

